  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international efforts to address financial crimes\n- Limited scope and enforcement\n\n2. Key Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Introduction of international anti-money laundering standards\n- Increased international cooperation and information sharing\n\n3. Major Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Enhanced financial institution regulations\n- Stricter customer due diligence\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Risk-based approach to compliance\n- Advanced technological solutions for detecting suspicious activities\n\n5. Global Regulatory Landscape\n- Comprehensive Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border collaboration\n- Increased transparency in financial systems\n\n6. Recent Developments\n- Beneficial ownership registries\n- Enhanced whistleblower protections\n- More sophisticated data analytics\n- Focus on emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legislative approach continues to evolve, adapting to new financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
